{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488256","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488256"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:34:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:34:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"395"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/395"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.49,0.06,0.06,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"395"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109884"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/395"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"395"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92245"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3685"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8348"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9200"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27535"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41221"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109884","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109884"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department following a severe traumatic brain injury after a fall at a construction site and is admitted to intensive care requiring mechanical ventilation. A femoral vein central venous catheter is inserted soon after admission to assist with resuscitation. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFive days later, he develops a fever of 38.5\u00b0C. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on mechanical ventilation, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. His neurological deficits remain unchanged since admission. There are no signs of respiratory failure, abdominal tenderness, or skin and soft tissue infection. The central line insertion site appears clean.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood cultures have been drawn. Urine and sputum microscopy and culture are normal. A chest radiograph is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following organisms is most likely to be isolated on blood cultures?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Coagulase-negative Staphylococci","Escherichia coli","Streptococcus pneumoniae","Candida albicans"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with a central line-associated bloodstream infection (CLABSI). \u003Cstrong\u003ECoagulase-negative Staphylococci\u003C/strong\u003E are the most common causative organisms, accounting for 30-40% of CLABSIs. These organisms are normal skin flora that can colonise and form biofilms on central venous catheters, particularly when inserted under emergency conditions when there may be imperfect aseptic conditions, if there are multiple lumens or non-antibiotic coated lines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/strong\u003E can cause CLABSIs but is less common than coagulase-negative Staphylococci. It is more commonly associated with ventilator-associated pneumonia or hospital-acquired pneumonia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/strong\u003E is a common cause of urosepsis and intra-abdominal infections but is less commonly isolated in CLABSIs. The normal urinalysis and lack of abdominal symptoms make this organism less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes community-acquired pneumonia and meningitis. It would be unusual to cause a CLABSI, particularly with a normal chest radiograph.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECandida albicans\u003C/strong\u003E can cause CLABSIs but is more commonly seen in patients with prolonged antibiotic use, total parenteral nutrition, or immunosuppression, none of which are present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe femoral insertion site is a significant risk factor for line infection compared to other sites such as internal jugular or subclavian veins. Management typically involves line removal and appropriate antimicrobial therapy based on culture results.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Coagulase-negative Staphylococci are the most common cause of central line-associated bloodstream infections.","Femoral vein catheter insertion sites have a higher risk of infection compared to other sites.","Multiple positive blood cultures with skin commensals in a patient with a central line strongly suggests line-associated infection."],"references":["Surveillance of Central Line-Associated Bloodstream Infection [Internet]. ANZICs. 2019. Available from: https://www.anzics.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Implementation-Guide-Surveillance-of-CLABSI.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92245"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"395"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92245","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92245"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-27T13:16:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-27T13:17:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"395"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109884"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"t